column36: Gather all the supplies and prepare to go the route that was filed in the flight plan. Use all the recourses wisely. Take care of one another, so we won't  die in the heat or encounter a sticky situation. Most importantly is to stay calm and positive for the other person. Use the most important items first.
column136: Gather supplies, use map to locate nearest water source. Restrock on water, empty salt tablets in compress kit, use container for water. Depending on location of environment, find a safe place. Look for nearest habitation during middle of the night

column36: Find a source of water. After ranking the items on importance, we will start finding a way to the mining camp.

column36: attempt to signal any aircraft while trying to travel to the inhabited mining camp for help. short term plan is to stay hydrated for continued survival.  long term plan is to make it to the mining camp or another inhabited area such as a road in order to be rescued.

column36: Get through the day until the sun is going down.  Signal for help as a 70 mile walk is probably not feasible.  Besides the heat, possibly scorpions.  Thirst because of little bottled water.
column136: Stay by the plane for the first day. So stay put, scout area for anything needed - water, food, shelter, long term to signal and walk to mining town leave signal of traveled direction.

column36: Firstly, I think that is important to find items that will ensure our health and safety in short-term and long-term because even if we cannot save ourselves, the longer the time the more likely we'll be found. Next would be to gather items to help rescue ourselves.

column31: I need and use glasses.  I am currently wearing them.

column36: My strategy would be to get to some sort of town/civilization as soon and as fast as possible to get in contact with someone that is able to help us.  Notify the authorities of what happened and get the remains of the deceased victims.
column136: Immediate: to establish our safety and well-being so we are able to  work towards out long-term plan, which is to reach the mining site and seek help.

column36: The plan is to go find the mining camp because there has to be people there and to use the objects provided to get there as quickly as possible without getting injured or sick.

column36: Immediate plan: assess situation, injuries, terrain, determine whether or not it is feasible to contact any air control that might be following the progress of the flight.  Since that does not appear to be the case, long term plan: try to navigate to the mining camp and pray that it is currently inhabited.  Other long term plan: don't die of exposure or dehydration on the way to the mining camp.  ensure that while making choices of what items to bring I am considering both day desert survival and night desert survival.
column136:

column36:
1. 1 bottle of water per person (most important to stay hydrated)
2. magnetic compass (to know in what direction to go to find the mining camp)
3. sectional area map of the area (to also help with finding help)
4. the book (to help determine what we can eat while we find help)
5. jack knife (to help cut plants or animals to eat)
6. small pistol (also for food and for protection)
7. pair of sunglasses (to protect from sun)
8. flashlight (to see at night)
9. compress kit with gauze (to have in case of injury)
10. parachute (to use to make shelter)
11. vodka (start fire or injury)
12. plastic rain coat (if it rains? it is monsoon season)
13. salt tablets 
14. top coat (maybe to protect from heat but it would be too hot to wear)
15. cosmetic mirror (not necessary)

immediate plan would be to find the direction in which we need to start heading to find help and long-term plan would be to stay hydrated and find food along the way

concerns and dangers: not having enough water or food, becoming dehydrated, coming in contact with a coyote, snake or other dangerous animal

column36:
Since the area is flat, I believe the best decision would be to cut/fit the parachute to the frame of the plane or over surrounding shrubs in order to make a temporary shelter until we can get our bearings. We should also put the top coats on (assuming they are down or something cooler than the surroundings) to protect ourselves from direct sunlight. From our shelter, we need to map out where the mining camp is as well as any mountains. This may also be a good time to study what plants are edible in the area (we should only hunt animals after we can't find any plants since they will likely take far more effort). From here, if we can spot any mountains in the direction of the camp, we need to hike toward them (morning or night, preferably) in order to gain a better vantage point and hopefully use the mirror to signal any passing vehicles or planes. We need to keep the vodka on us in case of injury or in case one of us begins to experience heatstroke and needs to cool off immediately on our journey. The salt tablets will be used when we have sweat excessively and lost too many electrolytes. If we can, we should take the parachute with us or use our raincoats as shelter along the trip.
In the long term, we need to know more about what we can and cannot eat and we need to be able to gather water from plants along the way (possibly cut into the cactus?). The water should be rationed extensively, especially if we have no better means of gathering additional water other than from plants (if it rains we can use the raincoats to catch water and funnel it into the bottles). Should we decide hiking at night is better (we can see well enough and won't get lost), we should use the flashlight sparingly.

column36:
With the plane crash having occurred in the desert, our plan will include having to stick together to create a plan. The plan that I envision would involve us acknowledging that we have to conserve the bottled water and leave that under a shade so that the plastic doesn't come into direct sunlight, thus creating the water to be bad for us. 

The immediate plan that I would have would be to look at the map and see more or less where we are positioned with the compass, and see if the truly closest area is 70 miles away. With the gun, I'm not really sure what we would use it for but we would have to keep it around just in case.

The materials that are present I believe are now listed in the correct order of importance, the reason I feel that they have been listed in importance is because they offer immediate aid, the sunglasses shield our eyes from the sun, and the flashlight allows us to see the oncoming threats at night. 

The concern that I would have is us dying from heat and dying from lack of water, if all else fails, in our effort to make signals and "call" for help, we can just drink the vodka and die if it came to that, but I feel that would be the very last resort. If anything we can start walking while we have energy to search for water, or more importantly search for a highway, or a road. The plane can only shield us for so long. 

The coats and the rain coat aren't beneficial to us.
